	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105032735820?origin=resultslist},
	doi = {10.1109/CINTI67731.2025.11311850},
	abstract = {The concept of Robotics 4.0 represents the integration of robotic technologies with digital innovations within the broader framework of Industry 4.0. This paper analyzes the transition from traditional industrial robotics to intelligent, collaborative, and networked robotic systems, and examines their potential implementation in educational settings. Special attention is given to the integration of microcontrollers (Arduino, ESP32, Raspberry Pi Pico) and sensor modules in robotics education at secondary and higher education levels. The research section presents an experiment aimed at evaluating the effectiveness of project-based robotics education using microcontrollers, focusing on changes in students' technical skills, programming competencies, and motivation. The results highlight the importance of hands-on learning in preparing graduates for modern industry requirements and provide recommendations for effectively linking industrial practice with pedagogical processes. The study, conducted at a Slovak secondary school, examined the impact of project-based robotics education using the Arduino platform on students' technical and programming competencies as well as motivation (N=48). An eight-week intervention was implemented in a quasi-experimental design with pre- and posttests and a control group, employing a knowledge test, assessment rubric, and motivation questionnaire. Statistical analysis confirmed significant improvements across all evaluated areas in favor of the experimental group. © 2025 IEEE.},
