	title = {Student {Engagement} and {Motivation} toward {Education} 4.0},
	issn = {978-104058396-8 (ISBN); 978-104106006-2 (ISBN)},
	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105037228395?origin=resultslist},
	doi = {10.1201/9781003633433-3},
	abstract = {Over the past three centuries, our world has undergone four transformative industrial revolutions. Education 4.0 has emerged as a ubiquitous concept in contemporary educational discourse. In addition to 21st-century skills, students need to be comfortable with developing technology and able to use it to their advantage for their growth and development, and apply it to solve their personal, workplace, and societal problems. Students bring unique perspectives and meaningful connections to academic pursuits, infusing them with personal significance that drives their energy and focus in diverse ways. This energy and focus are called motivation. Increasing student engagement promotes learning, retention, and academic success. Motivating and actively engaging students beyond getting their degree, building their life and career for the next 30 years after graduation, and making them realize they are lifelong self-learners are the present challenges and opportunities in higher education, along with localized educational and social issues. Students need to be motivated to involve themselves and actively engage to develop higher-order thinking skills, learn how to learn, practice metacognition, and understand transdisciplinary subjects to solve societal problems. Three types of transformations—technological, strategic, and learner characteristics transformations—are identified and discussed by the author to enhance student engagement and motivation toward Education 4.0. © 2026 selection and editorial matter, Samsul Ariffin Abdul Karim, Chockalingam Aravind Vaithilingam and Ari Happonen; individual chapters, the contributors.},
	language = {English},
