	issn = {978-139441128-3 (ISBN); 978-183669010-8 (ISBN)},
	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105023246527?origin=resultslist},
	doi = {10.1002/9781394411283.ch9},
	abstract = {The Fourth Industrial Revolution (4IR) presents new technical novelties that have altered social relations and sectors of the economy. This chapter shows how higher education institutions (HEIs) balance autonomy and regulation when responding to emerging 4IR technologies. Artificial intelligence, Big Data, blockchain, virtual reality and augmented reality are disruptive technologies that HEIs are forced to incorporate into their curricula in this new environment. These tools have the potential to transform instructional strategies, customize learning and increase administrative effectiveness. Institutions that have autonomy can modify their programmes to accommodate the quickly changing demands of both the labor market and students. The chapter discusses various successful cases to offer information that may be important to current regulatory bodies, academic institutions and politicians. Universities that effectively establish the right combination of autonomy and control mechanisms are in a position to train their graduates for the fourth industrial revolutionary workforce, which contributes positively to the development of society. © ISTE Ltd 2025.},
